06103nam a22007935i 9780824893774DE-B159720230502090707.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230502t20222023hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a2022043602  a97808248937747 a10.1515/97808248937742doi  a(DE-B1597)618915  a(OCoLC)1356995416  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI00aDS799.3b.P43 2023 4aDS799.3 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a931/.249223/eng/20220926eng1 aPearson, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTaiwan Archaeology :bLocal Development and Cultural Boundaries in the China Seas /cRichard Pearson. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2022] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (286 p.) :b5 color, 36 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1 Frameworks and Debates -- tChapter 2 Environment of Taiwan, Fujian, Guangdong, Hong Kong , and the Ryukyu Islands -- tChapter 3 Palaeolithic Discoveries -- tChapter 4 Early Neolithic, 6500 to 4500 BP -- tChapter 5 Middle Neolithic, 4500 to 3500 BP -- tChapter 6 Late Neolithic, 3500 to 2500 BP -- tChapter 7 Metal Period, 2500 to 500 BP -- tChapter 8 Contact Period, AD 1500 to 1663 -- tChapter 9 Taiwan in Context The Archaeology of Neighboring Fujian, Guangdong, Hong Kong, and the Ryukyu Islands -- tChapter 10 Conclusions and Prospects -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Taiwan Archaeology: Local Development and Cultural Boundaries in the China Seas, Richard Pearson describes the archaeology of the island, outlining the major discoveries of the past fifty years. These date from roughly 200,000 years ago to the pivotal seventeenth century AD, the time of Dutch and Spanish contact and the entry of Taiwan into global trade markets. The book focuses on some forty sites and is based on roughly 450 published sources in English, Chinese, and Japanese and includes a brief discussion of finds from the surrounding areas of Fujian, Guangdong, the northern Philippines, and the Ryukyu Islands, noting their significance for understanding Taiwan. This discussion allows for comparison of the different historical trajectories of the neighboring regions of the East and South China Seas through more than five millennia. While the early chapters are primarily descriptive with some interpretive conclusions, the final chapter contains discussions of general topics that integrate and interpret the earlier narrative sections and highlight some of the most interesting topics of the latest research, such as the effects of sea level change, ancient exchange systems of basalt from Penghu and nephrite from Fengtian (Hualien) and glass beads from Southeast Asia and the China mainland. The prehistoric people of Taiwan lived in a similar fashion to the peoples of the adjacent mainland until around 3500 years ago, when their cultural and political developmental trajectories of development diverged, as Taiwan became isolated from the increasingly complex societies of Guangdong and Fujian. New data show that southern and eastern Taiwan groups participated in exchange networks with people in Island Southeast Asia as early as 2500 years ago. Unique in its coverage of recent advances in the study of the long-term history of Taiwan and surrounding areas, Taiwan Archaeology explores many features of the island’s premodern past that are key to understanding its current geopolitical situation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aAntiquities, PrehistoriczTaiwan. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zTaiwan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMP